## Building on the Architecture

Yesterday I mapped out the technical architecture of OpenMRS on AWS — EC2, RDS, S3, VPC, security groups. Today I went a level deeper and asked a more specific question: once you understand what components exist, what does it actually take to handle the patient data flowing through them in a way that is both legally compliant and genuinely secure?

This is where compliance gets concrete. It is not enough to know that HIPAA requires data protection. You need to know exactly what that means for each component in your architecture — which services need encryption, what agreements need to be in place with your cloud provider, and which controls are your responsibility versus AWS's.

---

## What I Worked On Today

The starting point for HIPAA compliance on AWS is something called a **Business Associate Agreement — or BAA**.

Under HIPAA, any third party that handles electronic protected health information (ePHI) on behalf of a covered entity is called a **Business Associate**. When a healthcare organization uses AWS to host a system like OpenMRS — where patient data is stored and processed — AWS becomes a Business Associate. And HIPAA requires that a formal written agreement be in place between the covered entity and any Business Associate before ePHI is shared.

The BAA defines what AWS is permitted to do with the data, what security obligations it accepts, and what happens in the event of a breach. Without a signed BAA, using AWS to process or store ePHI is a HIPAA violation — regardless of how well the technical controls are configured.

AWS makes its BAA available through **AWS Artifact** — a compliance portal within the AWS console where you can review and accept the agreement. This was one of the practical exercises I worked through today, and it reinforced something important: compliance in the cloud is not just a technical exercise. It starts with understanding and fulfilling the legal and contractual requirements before a single line of configuration is written.

One thing I want to be clear about — and this connects directly back to the shared responsibility model from Day 16 — signing a BAA with AWS does not transfer your compliance obligations to AWS. It establishes that AWS will protect the infrastructure it controls. Everything within the customer's responsibility — configuration, access management, encryption settings, audit logging — remains the customer's obligation. The BAA is necessary but nowhere near sufficient.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most today is the relationship between the BAA and the technical controls. They are two separate layers of the same compliance requirement, and both are essential.

The BAA is the legal layer. It establishes the contractual framework that makes it permissible to use AWS for ePHI under HIPAA. Without it, you are legally exposed regardless of how secure your technical configuration is.

The technical controls are the operational layer. They are what actually protect the data in practice. A signed BAA with no encryption, no access controls, and no audit logging satisfies the paperwork requirement of HIPAA while completely failing the security requirement. That is the compliance-security gap from Day 15 showing up again — this time in a very specific cloud compliance context.

Real HIPAA compliance on AWS requires both: the legal agreement that makes the arrangement permissible, and the technical controls that make the arrangement actually safe.

