## Encryption — What It Means for Each Component

Encryption is one of the most important technical controls for ePHI in the cloud, and today I tried to understand exactly what it means for each component of the OpenMRS architecture:

**RDS — Database Encryption at Rest**
AWS RDS supports encryption using AES-256 through AWS Key Management Service (KMS). When enabled, the database files, automated backups, snapshots, and read replicas are all encrypted. Importantly, encryption must be enabled at the time the RDS instance is created — it cannot be added retroactively to an existing unencrypted instance. For an OpenMRS deployment handling patient records, this is non-negotiable.

**S3 — Backup and File Storage Encryption**
S3 supports server-side encryption for all objects stored in a bucket. AWS offers several encryption options — SSE-S3 uses AWS-managed keys, SSE-KMS uses customer-managed keys through KMS for additional control and audit capability. For backup data containing patient records, SSE-KMS is the stronger choice because it provides an audit trail of key usage through CloudTrail. S3 bucket policies should also enforce that all objects are encrypted at upload — rejecting any upload that does not include encryption headers.

**EBS — Volume Encryption**
The EC2 instance running OpenMRS uses Elastic Block Store (EBS) volumes for its operating system and application files. EBS encryption ensures that data written to these volumes is encrypted at rest. Like RDS, EBS encryption should be enabled at the time the volume is created, and AWS now supports setting encryption as the default for all new EBS volumes in an account.

**In Transit — HTTPS and TLS**
All data moving between users and the OpenMRS application, and between the application and the database, should be encrypted in transit using TLS. For user-facing traffic this means enforcing HTTPS and redirecting any HTTP requests. For database connections this means requiring SSL/TLS on the RDS connection string and rejecting unencrypted connections.

