## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2022 Baptist Medical Center and Resolute Health Hospital breach** — a ransomware attack that affected approximately 1.2 million patients. The investigation found that attackers had accessed the network and were able to reach sensitive data in part because of gaps in access controls and network segmentation.

What made this case relevant to today's topic is the post-breach regulatory focus. HHS investigators examining the organization's HIPAA compliance looked not just at whether policies existed, but at whether the technical controls — encryption, access management, audit logging — were actually in place and functioning. Having a BAA with cloud service providers was a baseline expectation. What investigators scrutinized was whether the operational security practices matched the compliance documentation.

This is the pattern I keep seeing: the compliance documentation and the technical reality need to match. A BAA signed and filed, combined with an unencrypted RDS database and no CloudTrail logging, is not HIPAA compliance. It is paperwork on top of a security gap. The technical controls are what make the compliance real.

